The mean value of facial skin temperature scanned by IRT was 35.1 °C and that of axillary temperature measured by thermometer was 37.8 °C. The difference between these temperatures was 2.7 °C, which was greater than the difference of 1.6 °C between IRT set point (35.4 °C) and axillary temperature (37.0 °C). This shows the possibilities of IRT detecting false negatives for febrile subjects. Figure 4 shows the correlation plot of the facial skin temperatures monitored by IRT and the axillary temperatures measured by thermometer. The IRT measurement exhibited a positive correlation with that of the thermometer (r = 0.60); the linear least square fitting equation is as follows:
